    .groupsite_blue.subtitle.is-3[data-search-target="result"]
      |  Uploading files 
    .groupsite_blue.subtitle.is-5[data-search-target="result"]
      |  Files can uploaded to the File Cabinet. Maximum file size is 175MB. Files can be uploaded to the File Cabinet through the drag and drop feature. By clicking and uploading a file from your computer, or by adding a file to a feature, such as the Dashboard. 
    ul
      li[data-search-target="result"]
        |  Dragging and Dropping - Once logged into your group do the following. 
        ol
          li
            |  Click 
            b
              | "Files"
          li
            |  select a 
            b
              | folder
          li
            b
              | drag
            |  a file from your computer to the section 
            b
              | "DRAG OR CLICK HERE TO UPLOAD"
            | . 
      li[data-search-target="result"]
        |  Single File Upload - Once logged into your group do the following. 
        ol
          li
            |  Click 
            b
              | "Files"
          li
            |  select a 
            b
              | folder
          li
            |  click 
            b
              | "DRAG OR CLICK HERE TO UPLOAD"
          li
            |  Select a 
            b
              | specific folder
            |  to upload into 
          li
            |  click 
            b
              | "Upload File(s) into..."
            | . 
      li[data-search-target="result"]
        |  When adding a single file on the various features, such as the Dashboard, Discussions, Media Gallery, Blogs, etc. a folder is created in the File Cabinet that is viewable only to managers, but can not be modified. These folders are used by the platform to display the files in its relative feature. The folders will have a key symbol on them and titled "User Created Content". 


    .groupsite_blue.subtitle.is-3[data-search-target="result"]
      |  Uploading files to the Dashboard/Displaying Images and Videos. To use a file on the Dashboard from the File Cabinet, it must first be uploaded to the File Cabinet. 
    br
    .groupsite_blue.subtitle.is-5[data-search-target="result"]
      |  The following dashboard modules can be used to upload links to preview files or display images and videos. The modules are Text Module, Free Text(HTML) Module, Media Gallery Module, and File Cabinet Files Module. 
    ul
      li[data-search-target="result"]
        b[style="color:#1A59CC"]
          |  Text Module 
        ol
          li
            |  click 
            b
              | "Free Text"
          li
            |  under "Event Details" in the header click 
            b
              | one of last two icons
            | . 
            ul
              li
                |  The 
                b
                  | paper clip icon
                |  will attach files from your computer and will be 
                b
                  | displayed as an image or video
                |  on the dashboard. 
              li
                |  The last icon, the 
                b
                  | file browser
                |  will choose a file from the group's File Cabinet, and will 
                b
                  | show a link
                |  that once clicked will display the file. Files that can not be processed by the browser will need to be downloaded to be viewed completely. Such as Excel or Power Point. 
      li[data-search-target="result"]
        b[style="color:#1A59CC"]
          | Free Text(HTML) Module
        |  - Using this module you could control how the size of the image/s or Video/s are displayed. The address/URL to the image is needed. You would be able to provide a URL to image or use an image hosted in your group's file cabinet feature. To use an image from the file Cabinet, first obtain the URL to the file. Second, go to the dashboard and add a free text module. When adding the module, an HTML 
        img
        |  tag would need to be used. The following are steps to use an HTML img and video tag. 
      ol
        li[data-search-target="result"]
          b
            | Obtain the address of the file's location
          | . To get a file's location from the group's file cabinet using the dashboard's Free Text(HTML) module do the following 
          ol
            li
              |  Click 
              b
                | "File Cabinet"
            li
              |  find the 
              b
                | image
              |  desired 
            li
              |  scroll over the 
              b
                | 3 horizontal dots
              |  to the right of the file 
            li
              |  click 
              b
                | "Share"
            li
              b
                | copy
              |  the link. The copied link will be used as the source for displaying the file. 
        li[data-search-target="result"]
          |  Create Free Text(HTML) Module with &lt;img&gt; and &lt;video&gt; tags - 
          ul
            li[data-search-target="result"]
              |  Once the URL is copied do the following. 
              ol
                li
                  |  click 
                  b
                    | "Add Module"
                  |  on the dashboard 
                li
                  |  click 
                  b
                    | "Free Text(HTML)"
                li
                  b
                    | Add a title
                  |  in the "Title" field 
                li
                  |  in the "HTML Code" field add an &lt;img&gt; or &lt;video&gt; tag and paste the 
                  b
                    | copied URL
                  |  as as the src. In the following example paste the copied URL where it says 
                  b
                    i
                      | COPIED_URL
                  |  before 
                  b
                    | /preview
                  | . 
              - # &#60;img src="COPIED_URL/preview"&#62;.
              div[style="display:flex;flex-flow:row wrap;" data-controller="clipboard"]
                span[data-clipboard-target="source"]
                  b
                    |  Example 
                    = @copy_image
                button.button.example.is-primary[data-action="clipboard#copy"]
                  |  Copy Example 
                span.hidden[style="color:red;background-style:bold;" data-clipboard-target="message"]
                  |  Copied! 
            li[data-search-target="result"]
              |  By adding a width and height attribute to the image would allow some control over the size of the image displayed. Place the copied file's URL between the parenthesis after src and add /preview. Example is as follows, &lt;img src="FILE'S_URL/preview" width="600" height="500"&gt;. Note the image will maintain the same aspect ratio. 
            li[data-search-target="result"]
              |  Some things to note. 
              ul
                li[data-search-target="result"]
                  |  To display images and videos /preview needs to be added to the copied file's URL. The following example uses an img tag. Paste your file's URL/address, where it says COPIED_URL before /preview 
                  - # &#60;img src="https://FILE_URL/files/1106075/preview"&#62;
                  div[style="display:flex;flex-flow:row wrap;" data-controller="clipboard"]
                    span[data-clipboard-target="source"]
                      b
                        |  Example 
                        = @copy_image
                    button.button.example.is-primary[data-action="clipboard#copy"]
                      |  Copy Example 
                    span.hidden[style="color:red;background-style:bold;" data-clipboard-target="message"]
                      |  Copied! 
                li[data-search-target="result"]
                  |  The tag to use to display an image. In the following example paste the file's URL/address, where it says COPIED_URL before /preview. 
                  div[style="display:flex;flex-flow:row wrap;" data-controller="clipboard"]
                    span[data-clipboard-target="source"]
                      b
                        |  Example 
                        = @copy_image
                    button.button.example.is-primary[data-action="clipboard#copy"]
                      |  Copy Example 
                    span.hidden[style="color:red;background-style:bold;" data-clipboard-target="message"]
                      |  Copied! 
                  - # &#60;img src="FILE'S_URL/preview"&#62;
                li[data-search-target="result"]
                  |  The tag to use to display a video. In the following example paste the file's URL/address, where it says FILE_URL before /preview. 
                  div[style="display:flex;flex-flow:row wrap;" data-controller="clipboard"]
                    span[style="display:flex;flex-flow:row wrap;" data-clipboard-target="source"]
                      b
                        |  Example 
                        = @copy_video
                    button.button.example.is-primary[data-action="clipboard#copy"]
                      |  Copy Example 
                    span.hidden[style="color:red;background-style:bold;" data-clipboard-target="message"]
                      |  Copied! 
                  - # &#60;video width="1OO" height="100" controls&#62; &#60;source src="FILE'S_URL/preview"&#62; &#60;/video&#62;. Tag attributes can be adjusted as needed.
                li[data-search-target="result"]
                  |  width and height attributes can be used to adjust the sizing of the image or video. Example &lt;img src="FILE'S_URL/preview" width="50%" height="50%"&gt; 
      li[data-search-target="result"]
        b[style="color:#1A59CC"]
